1
00:00:01,060 --> 00:00:17,937
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambudassa

2
00:00:18,559 --> 00:00:31,556
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble, and fully Self-Enlightened One.

3
00:00:34,219 --> 00:00:44,773
So, we are gathered here today to commemorate the life and work of the Buddha himself, our founder.

4
00:00:45,734 --> 00:00:46,896
I'm going to actually...

5
00:00:47,905 --> 00:00:49,866
I just talked more about his teaching.

6
00:00:49,906 --> 00:00:56,475
But remember this was a kernel event in the life of humanity.

7
00:00:57,476 --> 00:01:02,182
There's no reason to believe that he was the first one to experience Nibbana.

8
00:01:02,323 --> 00:01:04,545
He talked of it as an ancient path.

9
00:01:05,826 --> 00:01:09,171
But he was definitely one who came along and

10
00:01:09,504 --> 00:01:15,736
began to teach it in a way that was very open to even different cultures.

11
00:01:16,236 --> 00:01:29,962
In terms of world religions, complete world religions that have transgressed, that have spread through different cultures, really you've only got the three, haven't you?

12
00:01:30,022 --> 00:01:31,986
Christianity, Islam and Buddhism.

13
00:01:33,367 --> 00:01:41,435
And remember that his discovery was such that he was able to step out of the culture of his time.

14
00:01:41,775 --> 00:01:49,341
So he stepped out of the Brahminical tradition of the Vedas and was able to establish his own teaching.

15
00:01:50,944 --> 00:01:53,186
The Jain leader also was able to do that.

16
00:01:53,646 --> 00:01:56,368
So it wasn't as though he was unique in that.

17
00:01:56,688 --> 00:02:02,935
But definitely the manner of his teaching and the perception of his insight was such that

18
00:02:02,915 --> 00:02:11,587
We don't find anything deeper than that, I think, in any other religious form.

19
00:02:12,229 --> 00:02:19,679
So we've come to really celebrate that, the fact that we are receivers of that teaching.

20
00:02:21,741 --> 00:02:25,127
And remember that he himself had to discover it.

21
00:02:25,647 --> 00:02:28,973
It's not as though he was born with that innate understanding.

22
00:02:29,391 --> 00:02:37,021
that he went through the whole process of the purification of the heart and the insights necessary for liberation.

23
00:02:38,098 --> 00:02:46,948
And most of us, I'm sure all of you know the story, the kernel points were leaving the homely life, the household life.

24
00:02:48,150 --> 00:02:54,536
So this must have been quite a break for him, especially since his only child had just been born.

25
00:02:55,516 --> 00:03:02,204
But that shows you the manner of his state of mind at the time, which we have to be, shall we say, compassionate with.

26
00:03:03,185 --> 00:03:07,650
These days we can't understand why anybody should leave their family like that.

27
00:03:07,933 --> 00:03:10,498
But then, of course, it was an extended family.

28
00:03:10,519 --> 00:03:12,603
It wasn't as though she was left high and dry.

29
00:03:12,622 --> 00:03:21,258
And he must have been in a state of severe inner turmoil, what we would call an existential crisis.

30
00:03:22,581 --> 00:03:24,205
And it was that that really drove him.

31
00:03:25,213 --> 00:03:40,431
Remember that he tries all the forms that the age was able to offer him, all the yoga forms that were there, the development of mental states that we call absorptions.

32
00:03:42,953 --> 00:03:45,536
And he found that wanting only because they came to an end.

33
00:03:46,016 --> 00:03:51,862
So these are still belonging to the phenomenal world, the world of the mind.

34
00:03:52,213 --> 00:03:54,037
And then he tried self-mortification.

35
00:03:54,276 --> 00:04:12,586
So this was based on that basic understanding that the body itself was a manifestation of bad karma, manifestation of unwholesome actions that we'd done in the past, in the past lives, and that it was holding the soul down.

36
00:04:12,967 --> 00:04:19,858
So the whole process was letting go of the body, by which we mean letting go of the appetites of the body.

37
00:04:19,838 --> 00:04:25,004
So in a sense, blaming the body for the problems that we have.

38
00:04:25,406 --> 00:04:28,769
So if we had no appetite, then we wouldn't be suffering from greed.

39
00:04:28,829 --> 00:04:30,733
It was that sort of mentality.

40
00:04:31,915 --> 00:04:41,327
The Buddha tried that, of course, especially severe mortification in terms of food.

41
00:04:41,408 --> 00:04:45,312
He said he could hold his spine through his stomach.

42
00:04:45,793 --> 00:04:48,057
So if you try that, you'll see how thin he was.

43
00:04:48,238 --> 00:04:53,343
And then he gave that up because he discovered it simply to be more suffering.

44
00:04:53,783 --> 00:04:55,565
It didn't seem to be getting him anywhere.

45
00:04:56,747 --> 00:04:58,288
And with that, of course, he leaves.

46
00:04:58,348 --> 00:04:59,389
He leaves his companions.

47
00:05:00,230 --> 00:05:04,855
And we find him on the roadside, feeling, I should think, pretty miserable for himself.

48
00:05:05,536 --> 00:05:08,598
And along comes a woman, gives him some sweetmeats.

49
00:05:09,399 --> 00:05:10,680
And this revives him.

50
00:05:11,502 --> 00:05:16,947
And he has that memory from childhood where he's watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

51
00:05:16,927 --> 00:05:22,862
And that memory gives him a sort of an inkling as it turns his whole practice around.

52
00:05:23,442 --> 00:05:30,420
Instead of trying to achieve happiness, he then turns upon himself and tries to investigate the cause of his suffering.

53
00:05:30,439 --> 00:05:32,826
And it's with that inspiration that he sits under the tree.

54
00:05:33,177 --> 00:05:48,266
But even then, under the tree, there's this huge doubt, this huge doubt about whether he, in fact, has any right to continue this, to achieve anything beyond the human state, whether there is anything beyond the human state.

55
00:05:49,697 --> 00:06:03,228
And in the mythology that surrounds it, he touches the earth to ground himself, and the earth goddess arises and says that he's every right to do this because he has the perfection of generosity.

56
00:06:03,990 --> 00:06:05,771
So in other words, he's not doing it just for himself.

57
00:06:06,351 --> 00:06:19,603
And it was with that feeling that he was doing it not just for himself, but for everybody he knew, perhaps for the whole of humanity and all beings, that he found the courage to sort of break through that delusion.

58
00:06:20,072 --> 00:06:23,656
and then he experiences Nibbani bliss.

59
00:06:24,658 --> 00:06:30,504
Now, in that process, we say he has three knowledges.

60
00:06:30,665 --> 00:06:37,531
The first knowledge was that he has completely transcended, well, completely purified the heart.

61
00:06:37,793 --> 00:06:44,439
So there's no more aversion and all the aspects of aversion, fear, etc.

62
00:06:44,480 --> 00:06:46,642
There's no depression or anything like that.

63
00:06:46,942 --> 00:06:48,004
There's no greed whatsoever.

64
00:06:48,237 --> 00:06:57,747
And there's no more delusion about who he actually really is or what that is beyond this phenomenal form, this form of a human being.

65
00:06:58,449 --> 00:07:01,771
There's no doubt in his mind after that.

66
00:07:01,791 --> 00:07:11,122
Now, shortly after that, he then thinks about teaching and he gets this doubt as to whether anybody can understand the subtlety of what he's just discovered.

67
00:07:12,064 --> 00:07:21,285
And then again, it's put mythologically that this great god, Sampati, came down and said, look, there are some people with only a little dust in their eyes.

68
00:07:21,706 --> 00:07:24,773
So he reflected on it and he thought, well, I'll give it a go.

69
00:07:24,812 --> 00:07:28,540
And then he thought of his six companions, whom he then goes in search of.

70
00:07:28,641 --> 00:07:32,149
But on the way, he meets Upaka, I think that's his name.

71
00:07:32,129 --> 00:07:42,281
another ascetic, and Upaka says, oh, you know, you look very bright, you've got this lovely serene feeling about you.

72
00:07:42,401 --> 00:07:44,084
I said, who is your teacher?

73
00:07:44,463 --> 00:07:53,235
And the Buddha announces himself as the fully liberated one, the fully enlightened one, I don't have a teacher, etc., etc.

74
00:07:53,875 --> 00:07:57,579
And Upaka sort of shakes his head and says, oh, very good, okay, and then moves on.

75
00:07:58,689 --> 00:08:02,295
So I think you learn very quickly that's not quite how you get the Dharma across.

76
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:03,807
So he...

77
00:08:04,747 --> 00:08:11,235
Remember that just because he's fully liberated doesn't mean that he actually can teach.

78
00:08:11,314 --> 00:08:12,576
It's something that evolves.

79
00:08:12,677 --> 00:08:14,137
And you can see it in his teaching.

80
00:08:15,379 --> 00:08:20,826
The first teachings are not so rigidly formulated into four of these and five of those.

81
00:08:21,887 --> 00:08:25,831
In the scriptures you can see very early on it's coming out spontaneously.

82
00:08:26,011 --> 00:08:29,274
And then over time it becomes very formalized.

83
00:08:29,314 --> 00:08:32,899
Four noble truths, eightfold path, and so on and so forth.

84
00:08:33,993 --> 00:08:40,669
And then he spends the rest of his life, as you know, wandering around North India teaching the Dharma.

85
00:08:40,690 --> 00:08:49,673
So now the reading today begins with the way that he used to teach lay people, which may be of interest to you.

86
00:08:51,052 --> 00:08:54,336
And it was said that he always gave them a step-by-step discourse.

87
00:08:55,538 --> 00:09:01,346
And the first thing he talked about was giving, was generosity.

88
00:09:02,528 --> 00:09:05,192
So I'll go back to his particular experience.

89
00:09:05,211 --> 00:09:10,839
His whole courage, you might say, was based upon the fact that he wasn't just doing it for himself.

90
00:09:11,440 --> 00:09:16,486
He found that extra energy that he needed to stay under that tree and work.

91
00:09:16,466 --> 00:09:18,330
and continue his investigation.

92
00:09:19,010 --> 00:09:26,783
Now, although it doesn't say this in the scriptures, in the commentary it points out that giving itself is a path to liberation.

93
00:09:27,063 --> 00:09:31,191
Just giving itself, just generosity itself is a path to liberation.

94
00:09:32,472 --> 00:09:33,134
Now, why is that?

95
00:09:33,815 --> 00:09:37,000
When you give something, you necessarily have to renounce it.

96
00:09:38,062 --> 00:09:40,686
You know, something that you might have used for yourself,

97
00:09:41,999 --> 00:09:49,292
so much money that you might give to a charity, you could have given to yourself for your own benefit, for your own enjoyment.

98
00:09:50,081 --> 00:09:51,683
Time.

99
00:09:52,024 --> 00:09:57,192
You could have spent the time on something that you particularly like, but you're giving it up in order to help somebody.

100
00:09:57,852 --> 00:10:14,115
So that process of renunciation, you see, is also a way of undermining this selfishness, this constantly looking after ourselves, which is a product of that basic delusion that we have about who we are.

101
00:10:15,513 --> 00:10:23,802
And this giving is always easier when we have it on a base of gratitude.

102
00:10:24,793 --> 00:10:36,745
So when you consider all the gifts and blessings that you've received in this life, and that some of them have come without your asking, just the very fact of being born was a gift.

103
00:10:37,325 --> 00:10:40,768
How our mothers and fathers looked after us, this was all a gift.

104
00:10:41,389 --> 00:10:42,490
We never paid for it.

105
00:10:42,629 --> 00:10:43,171
Perhaps we should.

106
00:10:43,791 --> 00:10:45,613
But anyway, we never paid.

107
00:10:45,633 --> 00:10:47,914
It was just given to us and we received it.

108
00:10:48,696 --> 00:10:54,801
And when you consider the education system and friends and all these people who at times have come to help,

109
00:10:54,780 --> 00:11:00,466
that sense of gratitude allows us to let go of things.

110
00:11:01,047 --> 00:11:20,366
And in letting go of our wealth, not all of it, of course, and in letting go of our time for the benefit of others, we're undermining the way that we tend always to think about me, me, me, you see, instead of we, instead of actually joining the community at some level or other.

111
00:11:21,629 --> 00:11:24,436
So giving, that was the first thing he said.

112
00:11:25,017 --> 00:11:29,288
And he said everybody could be generous, even a thief.

113
00:11:29,607 --> 00:11:34,440
So a thief can steal something from you and then very generously give it to somebody else.

114
00:11:35,821 --> 00:11:41,591
So it was sort of a universal virtue that anybody and everybody could actually practice.

115
00:11:42,152 --> 00:11:43,153
So that's where he began.

116
00:11:43,173 --> 00:11:55,855
And he began there because, of course, the development of giving is already undermining that hard sense of self.

117
00:11:55,835 --> 00:12:00,041
where a sense of self creates barriers.

118
00:12:00,520 --> 00:12:03,065
It doesn't like boundaries so much.

119
00:12:03,164 --> 00:12:07,309
It likes to enclose itself with safety.

120
00:12:08,292 --> 00:12:14,519
Remember the self at its deepest level is very fearful, it's very unsafe.

121
00:12:14,980 --> 00:12:18,905
For a start it knows it's going to die, which isn't a very happy thought.

122
00:12:18,885 --> 00:12:29,806
And therefore it feels safe, it feels grounded, it feels strong, it feels solid when it has lots of money and lots of friends and lots of power.

123
00:12:30,106 --> 00:12:33,373
And that's why we collect these things around us as best we can.

124
00:12:34,375 --> 00:12:41,467
And in letting go of that, you see, in letting go of that, we're undermining that sense of solidity about ourselves.

125
00:12:42,815 --> 00:12:51,432
And of course the advantage of that is letting go of all the problems that come with holding on to things.

126
00:12:52,774 --> 00:12:59,827
So remember there's a consequence to an indulgence in life.

127
00:12:59,807 --> 00:13:05,153
See, while we are very rich and very powerful and very famous and all that, that's fine.

128
00:13:05,774 --> 00:13:12,542
But, of course, it's afterwards when the things begin to decrease, whether just naturally by aging.

129
00:13:13,783 --> 00:13:25,895
Then we feel those consequences, the frustration that we feel when we can't get what we want and the grief at loss, the fear of loss anyway, that sort of underlying anxiety.

130
00:13:26,797 --> 00:13:29,139
And in our society, which is...

131
00:13:29,120 --> 00:13:36,330
so separate, so lifted away, you might say, from the ground of nature.

132
00:13:36,350 --> 00:13:40,134
I mean, this whole place is dependent on electricity.

133
00:13:40,895 --> 00:13:42,918
It's nothing to do with ordinary nature.

134
00:13:43,578 --> 00:13:46,283
And during winter, occasionally, the lights will go out.

135
00:13:46,363 --> 00:13:49,447
Everything just blows out for some reason.

136
00:13:50,349 --> 00:13:52,191
And suddenly you realize that

137
00:13:52,171 --> 00:13:53,813
You couldn't run this plant.

138
00:13:53,833 --> 00:13:56,298
In fact, I don't think I could live without electricity.

139
00:13:56,840 --> 00:14:08,761
So there's that point where we've created a certain safety, but we know that underneath it, it's a very shallow safety.

140
00:14:08,741 --> 00:14:11,384
it can suddenly disappear from us.

141
00:14:11,904 --> 00:14:22,956
And of course, if you live in certain parts of the world, such as now in Nepal, you see, there you are, you're on that tower, perhaps a tourist, and you're enjoying the view, and the whole thing starts to collapse around you.

142
00:14:23,736 --> 00:14:29,263
So it's not as though we're not aware of that somewhere within the psyche, you see.

143
00:14:29,442 --> 00:14:32,947
And that is an underlying pressure in our lives.

144
00:14:33,927 --> 00:14:38,192
And to undermine that, you see, you begin to let go, begin to let go.

145
00:14:39,504 --> 00:14:42,677
So that's where he would begin.

146
00:14:42,738 --> 00:14:47,135
He'd begin by expressing the importance of generosity.

147
00:14:48,466 --> 00:14:50,929
And then he would talk about moral virtue.

148
00:14:51,471 --> 00:15:00,783
So in Buddhist psychology, all our unwholesomeness is based upon a wrong understanding.

149
00:15:01,826 --> 00:15:11,780
And we have to have a certain compassion for ourselves there because we're born into the human state and we presume ourselves to be human beings.

150
00:15:11,841 --> 00:15:13,123
I mean, that's pretty straightforward.

151
00:15:13,659 --> 00:15:24,071
And in that presumption, you see, we are depending upon this physical form in order to gain happiness.

152
00:15:24,191 --> 00:15:25,091
Because that's all we want.

153
00:15:25,152 --> 00:15:26,192
We just want to be happy.

154
00:15:27,293 --> 00:15:37,304
But in so doing, we are creating that basis of unreliability.

155
00:15:37,284 --> 00:15:50,144
And because of that, we have this relationship to life of gathering things around us to make us feel solid, getting rid of anything which is going to undermine that.

156
00:15:50,183 --> 00:15:51,086
That's the aversion.

157
00:15:51,767 --> 00:15:54,129
And when something is too big, you run for it.

158
00:15:54,110 --> 00:15:54,971
So there's your fear.

159
00:15:55,351 --> 00:16:00,980
So there's your three basic attitudes to life because of this wrong understanding.

160
00:16:01,861 --> 00:16:04,186
Acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

161
00:16:04,986 --> 00:16:09,975
And this immediately leads us into wrong actions, wrong relationships.

162
00:16:11,557 --> 00:16:16,048
And that's where the problem comes, because then, of course, we're building up habits which are unwholesome.

163
00:16:16,889 --> 00:16:28,216
And when we act upon unwholesome habits, we get that second tier of unwholesomeness, which is to do with shame, guilt, remorse, etc., etc.

164
00:16:28,197 --> 00:16:30,442
So it all tumbles upon itself.

165
00:16:31,104 --> 00:16:47,421
And what he's saying is if you begin to really look at your moral life, your ethical life, and begin to chip away at that, you're also undermining this wrong understanding as to who we are.

166
00:16:49,527 --> 00:16:55,057
So that would be his second point to get across to people, the importance of sila.

167
00:16:55,418 --> 00:16:57,461
Now, I've talked about the negative side.

168
00:16:57,481 --> 00:16:58,784
It's the opposite too.

169
00:16:59,706 --> 00:17:02,272
The better word is ethics, really, rather than morality.

170
00:17:02,812 --> 00:17:08,063
Morality we tend to limit to doing what is unwholesome.

171
00:17:08,644 --> 00:17:11,670
But ethics is just about relationships.

172
00:17:11,886 --> 00:17:19,558
So our relationship has its negative side, but remember that we've also got to develop its positive side.

173
00:17:19,578 --> 00:17:25,949
And that's these illimitables, love in all its facets, compassion, sympathetic joy, and so on.

174
00:17:26,951 --> 00:17:29,955
So that's what he would be talking about.

175
00:17:30,375 --> 00:17:36,546
And then he would tell them that, in fact, in so doing, they would be entering the heavenly worlds.

176
00:17:38,469 --> 00:17:39,530
Now...

177
00:17:41,063 --> 00:17:48,395
The heavenly worlds are simply mirrors of what we experience as human beings.

178
00:17:48,997 --> 00:18:05,265
So in actually developing love within ourselves, in developing joy within ourselves, that's mirrored in some cosmological heavenly state.

179
00:18:05,701 --> 00:18:14,152
These days, for a lot of people, rebirth and being born in other states is a bit difficult to understand.

180
00:18:14,511 --> 00:18:16,575
And it's not necessary, of course, to believe it.

181
00:18:17,715 --> 00:18:26,326
But generally speaking, I think the better position is not to come to a conclusion.

182
00:18:26,948 --> 00:18:34,576
Because if there happens to be other worlds, then we're in for a bit of a surprise or a shock.

183
00:18:34,557 --> 00:18:35,519
one way or the other.

184
00:18:35,558 --> 00:18:39,346
So it's best just to leave that on the back burner, as they say.

185
00:18:39,586 --> 00:18:40,989
And it may or may not happen.

186
00:18:42,352 --> 00:18:44,957
And the Buddha, of course, came across the same skepticism.

187
00:18:45,258 --> 00:18:46,740
And that's exactly what he says.

188
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:51,009
He says, look, if you practice the Dharma now, you'll get the benefits now.

189
00:18:51,890 --> 00:18:54,494
If there is a future life, then you'll get the benefits also.

190
00:18:54,796 --> 00:18:55,317
So...

191
00:18:56,224 --> 00:18:58,468
So it's not as though you have to believe these things.

192
00:18:59,489 --> 00:19:13,106
But it's good to know that the Buddha himself definitely did know about them because that was the other two knowledges that came to him at his liberation.

193
00:19:13,487 --> 00:19:25,843
The first was being able to go back to all his past lives and see very clearly that it was the ethical decisions he made which had the greatest effect on his future life.

194
00:19:26,836 --> 00:19:29,881
Now that's a breakthrough for the age, I'll explain that in a minute.

195
00:19:30,623 --> 00:19:36,673
And secondly, he saw other beings moving from one realm to the other according to the same law.

196
00:19:37,775 --> 00:19:42,042
So remember that at the time of the Buddha, the old

197
00:19:42,022 --> 00:19:51,051
Brahminical system, which was widespread in places like Rome, Greece, Mesopotamia, Egypt.

198
00:19:51,531 --> 00:19:54,035
It was this polytheism.

199
00:19:54,194 --> 00:19:59,400
It was this idea that there was a whole realm of gods that ruled the world.

200
00:20:00,560 --> 00:20:08,689
And that your job as a human being was to appease the gods, was to pray to them, to ask them for favours, etc., etc.

201
00:20:10,036 --> 00:20:19,871
And so in the Vedas and the Brahmins, even the Brahmins of that time, you would do these massive sacrifices to get what you wanted from the gods.

202
00:20:20,813 --> 00:20:31,368
And the sacrifices became really very refined rituals and you had to get everything right or else the god wouldn't respond.

203
00:20:31,348 --> 00:20:38,857
And of course these rituals weren't really delivering everything that they were expected to deliver.

204
00:20:39,057 --> 00:20:47,007
So there was a general losing of confidence in that whole process of polytheism.

205
00:20:48,268 --> 00:20:49,368
So it's to do with power.

206
00:20:49,549 --> 00:20:52,333
It wasn't to do with being good or bad.

207
00:20:52,353 --> 00:20:58,740
It was to do with you making the sacrifice to a particular god and getting what you wanted.

208
00:20:59,445 --> 00:21:05,233
So you can see the whole shift towards ethical life was quite a revolution.

209
00:21:05,835 --> 00:21:12,163
Where the Buddha's saying, no, if you want to get reborn in a happier place, it's to do with your ethics.

210
00:21:12,203 --> 00:21:13,346
It's not to do with these gods.

211
00:21:13,486 --> 00:21:16,108
It's not to do with the power of other deities.

212
00:21:21,917 --> 00:21:23,339
Yeah.

213
00:21:23,359 --> 00:21:25,722
So that's when he got on to.

214
00:21:26,123 --> 00:21:27,224
And then...

215
00:21:31,153 --> 00:21:36,145
And then he would talk about the dangers of this self of indulgence.

216
00:21:36,727 --> 00:21:46,951
So we've mentioned that really, that every time we indulge, what we're actually doing is creating a psychological dependency on something for our happiness.

217
00:21:46,932 --> 00:21:48,114
That's the problem, you see.

218
00:21:48,653 --> 00:21:52,720
I mean, if you just indulge and then you could let it go, that'd be fine.

219
00:21:53,381 --> 00:22:06,759
But when we indulge, we're actually placing a certain commitment to whatever it is that makes us happy at a psychological level.

220
00:22:07,260 --> 00:22:09,324
That's why it's so painful when it disappears.

221
00:22:09,344 --> 00:22:10,746
It doesn't matter what it is.

222
00:22:11,721 --> 00:22:19,757
So he's pointing out that's the dangers of that and the advantage of renouncing them.

223
00:22:20,480 --> 00:22:34,578
Here there's sometimes a confusion about what this renunciation means because it's not the same as what he was practicing when he was doing the self-mortification business because that was based on a completely different understanding.

224
00:22:35,059 --> 00:22:42,229
The idea of the soul being trapped in the body and letting go of the body meant that the soul could escape and rise to heaven.

225
00:22:43,730 --> 00:22:49,338
This was more in the sense of renouncing in order to undermine that belief

226
00:22:49,318 --> 00:22:56,173
that psychological dependency that grows with our indulgence.

227
00:22:56,692 --> 00:23:04,180
And remember that if you look at even the basic things, like on retreat here, we often look at this whole process around eating.

228
00:23:04,881 --> 00:23:14,770
But that attachment to porridge, for instance, I'm very attached, is translated.

229
00:23:14,851 --> 00:23:17,413
You see, it's the same psychology.

230
00:23:17,473 --> 00:23:18,013
That's the point.

231
00:23:18,375 --> 00:23:22,818
It's the same psychology no matter where you become attached.

232
00:23:22,798 --> 00:23:26,946
whether it's to art or nature or to a person.

233
00:23:27,729 --> 00:23:41,095
So when we undermine that, we think that we're actually also undermining our ability to enjoy pleasure and our ability to love.

234
00:23:41,699 --> 00:23:42,701
Because that's how it feels.

235
00:23:44,724 --> 00:23:49,313
Losing excitement, you see, feels like a loss.

236
00:23:50,695 --> 00:23:51,897
And we won't lose it.

237
00:23:52,519 --> 00:23:55,144
We won't want to lose it unless we see the aftermath.

238
00:23:55,404 --> 00:23:56,567
See, that's our problem.

239
00:23:58,089 --> 00:24:03,640
In a society where pleasure is just there at hand, you just turn the TV on for heaven's sake.

240
00:24:04,327 --> 00:24:12,319
We don't make the connection between the aftermath of indulgence with the actual process of indulging.

241
00:24:12,701 --> 00:24:14,763
So when we're indulging, what's the problem?

242
00:24:14,784 --> 00:24:16,226
We're enjoying life.

243
00:24:16,246 --> 00:24:20,031
It's the business that comes afterwards that we've mentioned, the frustration, etc.

244
00:24:20,593 --> 00:24:23,096
But also the sense of boredom.

245
00:24:23,144 --> 00:24:36,061
because the happiness that an object gives us, whether it's a person or food or whatever, has an inbuilt obsolescence.

246
00:24:36,102 --> 00:24:39,486
It begins to lose its flavour, you know, like chewing on the bedpost.

247
00:24:40,106 --> 00:24:41,750
And it just loses its flavour.

248
00:24:41,970 --> 00:24:44,553
So you can't keep scraping the chewing gum off and chewing it.

249
00:24:44,773 --> 00:24:50,821
So what you have to do is begin to feel, is begin to...

250
00:24:52,134 --> 00:24:59,647
accept that there's a loss of excitement and you have to, as it were, wait for the letting go.

251
00:24:59,708 --> 00:25:07,902
And when you've let go of something, you really do have to experience that moment of liberation.

252
00:25:09,885 --> 00:25:16,557
And it's catching the moment of liberation when you let go of something where you'll catch the deeper joy.

253
00:25:17,178 --> 00:25:24,334
See, what we do is we tend to let go of something, but we don't sort of hang on and wait for it to completely drop out of the system.

254
00:25:25,175 --> 00:25:25,375
See?

255
00:25:25,917 --> 00:25:27,922
And then you get that moment of liberation.

256
00:25:28,242 --> 00:25:30,969
Now, that moment of liberation is a taste of nibbana.

257
00:25:31,790 --> 00:25:34,215
That doesn't mean to say that the old habit doesn't come back.

258
00:25:34,355 --> 00:25:35,980
Of course it does.

259
00:25:35,960 --> 00:25:36,840
It's not that easy.

260
00:25:37,241 --> 00:25:40,045
But it's just letting go of something.

261
00:25:40,085 --> 00:25:40,685
Just try it.

262
00:25:40,786 --> 00:25:52,981
Anything that you are attached to at some level, just keep not feeding it and just wait for that moment when you feel it's just left the psyche, just gone like that.

263
00:25:53,522 --> 00:25:57,086
And it's that moment of liberation which has to be tasted.

264
00:25:57,528 --> 00:26:05,258
And once we begin to get a taste for that, you see, then it becomes easier and easier and easier to just let go of all the rest of it.

265
00:26:05,760 --> 00:26:12,070
But if it's always this struggle for letting go and then you fall back into the old habit, then it just becomes miserable.

266
00:26:12,471 --> 00:26:25,632
So make sure that if you are going to practice renunciation at any time, and you can do it at any time, just wait for that moment when you feel the release, the relief of it.

267
00:26:25,652 --> 00:26:26,452
That's very important.

268
00:26:29,115 --> 00:26:33,681
So that's the advantage of renouncing them.

269
00:26:33,701 --> 00:26:50,336
And then it says, when he felt that the mind was ready, open, without hindrances, inspired and confident, then he expounded to the listener the elevated Dharma teaching of the Buddhas, Dukkha, its origin, its cessation and the path.

270
00:26:50,657 --> 00:26:57,064
So, in other words, this teaching that he had to give, he felt he had to prepare himself

271
00:26:57,044 --> 00:27:00,710
He couldn't just go bang on in and say, look, life's suffering.

272
00:27:01,711 --> 00:27:03,374
You know, you need to do something about it.

273
00:27:03,875 --> 00:27:05,037
He just slowly prepares it.

274
00:27:05,877 --> 00:27:13,690
And he prepares it by pointing out that the path of liberation also has its joys.

275
00:27:14,171 --> 00:27:21,583
See, so we've talked about the joy of generosity, that very subtle joy of letting go.

276
00:27:21,563 --> 00:27:33,525
And the consequence of the ethical life, the feeling of the beautiful heart within us and the possibility of future beautiful rebirths.

277
00:27:33,924 --> 00:27:41,378
So with all that, you see, he's sort of got the person, he's whetted their appetite, you see, and then he tells them the truth.

278
00:27:41,499 --> 00:27:44,684
Life is suffering and horrible.

279
00:27:45,188 --> 00:27:47,732
Life is unsatisfactory.

280
00:27:47,913 --> 00:27:49,557
There is unsatisfactoriness.

281
00:27:50,317 --> 00:27:58,454
And so we'll also be reading the opening discourse that he gives about...

282
00:27:59,278 --> 00:28:00,099
about dukkha.

283
00:28:00,601 --> 00:28:05,507
Dukkha, remember, is that essential concept upon which the whole of his teaching is built.

284
00:28:06,468 --> 00:28:06,909
Dukkha.

285
00:28:07,348 --> 00:28:10,432
It means hard to bear in its basic meaning.

286
00:28:11,894 --> 00:28:13,017
Unsatisfactoriness.

287
00:28:13,616 --> 00:28:26,433
So it's always recognizing that life itself, although it brings its joys and pleasures, life itself holds its own sort of level of suffering.

288
00:28:26,413 --> 00:28:28,096
you know, aging and death.

289
00:28:28,436 --> 00:28:29,337
We can't escape that.

290
00:28:29,999 --> 00:28:39,111
And to make the distinction between the given, which is pain, and our reaction to it, our relationship to it, which is the suffering.

291
00:28:39,131 --> 00:28:41,273
So the Buddha always talks about two darts.

292
00:28:41,513 --> 00:28:42,895
See, the first dart is given.

293
00:28:43,336 --> 00:28:44,337
So you have a headache.

294
00:28:44,357 --> 00:28:45,239
That's given, you see.

295
00:28:45,579 --> 00:28:49,184
Now, how you react to your headache is an option.

296
00:28:49,605 --> 00:28:55,272
So you can either be very patient with it, or you can get angry with yourself for...

297
00:28:55,439 --> 00:28:56,160
having a headache.

298
00:28:56,680 --> 00:29:00,904
So he tries to make that distinction.

299
00:29:01,846 --> 00:29:13,257
And he talks about, you know, he begins by first of all pointing out these two extremes, by not falling into the error of these two extremes.

300
00:29:13,277 --> 00:29:14,377
So we've explained that.

301
00:29:14,919 --> 00:29:18,923
The one is to do with indulgence of pleasure and the other one is annihilation.

302
00:29:19,644 --> 00:29:24,028
The one to do with, sorry, self-mortification, right?

303
00:29:24,008 --> 00:29:26,152
So he's pointed that, the middle way.

304
00:29:26,612 --> 00:29:31,119
The middle way is actually not in between these two, it's transcendent of it.

305
00:29:31,540 --> 00:29:35,607
It's something that rises up above and is showing a particular path.

306
00:29:36,048 --> 00:29:41,156
And that, of course, is the Eightfold Path.

307
00:29:50,484 --> 00:29:54,623
He then goes on to the...

308
00:29:55,700 --> 00:30:00,164
dukkha, this is painful, it'll be read out, but I'm sure most of you have read it.

309
00:30:00,244 --> 00:30:06,813
Birth is painful, aging is painful, separation from what is liked is painful, not to get what one wants is painful, and so on.

310
00:30:07,453 --> 00:30:10,457
Then the reason for it, the unsatisfactoriness, is this craving.

311
00:30:10,877 --> 00:30:21,369
Now the craving is both for these sensual pleasures that we've been talking about, but it's also a craving to keep rebirthing ourselves.

312
00:30:21,349 --> 00:30:36,407
So when people ask me about rebirth, I say, well, if you actually see what's happening now in this present moment, from moment to moment, you won't have that much problem with the process of rebirth after death, because it's happening now.

313
00:30:37,509 --> 00:30:44,477
For instance, this body seems to us very solid, seems to us the same body that I woke up with this morning, for instance.

314
00:30:44,938 --> 00:30:49,163
But we all know that every seven years, every atom is completely changed.

315
00:30:49,143 --> 00:30:54,270
So next time you look at your face in the mirror, just remind yourself you weren't there seven years ago.

316
00:30:56,153 --> 00:30:58,178
You know what I mean?

317
00:30:58,198 --> 00:31:02,084
It's like recognizing that the body is constantly dying.

318
00:31:02,483 --> 00:31:05,328
It's constantly dying and being reborn.

319
00:31:05,308 --> 00:31:11,016
The mind, thoughts are constantly dying and being reborn.

320
00:31:11,155 --> 00:31:12,577
You get new thoughts every time.

321
00:31:12,917 --> 00:31:14,279
No thought is ever the same.

322
00:31:15,221 --> 00:31:18,404
Even if you were to say the same thing twice, it's not the same.

323
00:31:18,545 --> 00:31:20,768
If I said banana, banana.

324
00:31:21,509 --> 00:31:23,852
The second banana is not the first banana.

325
00:31:23,872 --> 00:31:24,692
It's completely different.

326
00:31:24,712 --> 00:31:27,856
It's another word, even though it means the same, etc.

327
00:31:27,836 --> 00:31:30,579
Our emotions never stop.

328
00:31:30,880 --> 00:31:34,684
They're constantly gurgling up from the depths.

329
00:31:35,265 --> 00:31:38,088
They can't be the same.

330
00:31:38,189 --> 00:31:40,171
You can't repeat anything in nature.

331
00:31:40,351 --> 00:31:46,657
Even though they might feel the same from a perceptual point of view, they're always different.

332
00:31:47,358 --> 00:31:52,545
This whole form is constantly rebirthing, moment after moment.

333
00:31:53,082 --> 00:31:58,696
And what keeps pushing that whole process is this attachment to this form.

334
00:31:59,479 --> 00:32:03,509
It's the belief that I am this human being.

335
00:32:04,171 --> 00:32:05,414
I am Bodhidharma.

336
00:32:05,434 --> 00:32:09,285
And anything that undermines that just makes me crazy.

337
00:32:11,205 --> 00:32:13,789
And then there's this craving for annihilation.

338
00:32:14,009 --> 00:32:17,355
Now, that's a completely different... That's the other process.

339
00:32:17,375 --> 00:32:19,617
That's the aversion side.

340
00:32:20,058 --> 00:32:24,285
That's when things get too much, you want to just get rid of yourself.

341
00:32:25,646 --> 00:32:31,635
When you've had a hard day or something, when you've been depressed, what do you do?

342
00:32:31,977 --> 00:32:34,539
You launch yourself onto the couch and disappear for a while.

343
00:32:35,561 --> 00:32:37,825
And that's a process of self-annihilation.

344
00:32:38,226 --> 00:32:40,368
The worst, of course, is suicide.

345
00:32:40,348 --> 00:32:51,067
So this whole process of getting rid of ourselves because we're fed up with ourselves at one level or another is the self trying to get rid of itself.

346
00:32:51,446 --> 00:32:53,230
Unfortunately, you always wake up.

347
00:32:53,651 --> 00:32:54,532
It's just one of those things.

348
00:32:55,493 --> 00:33:01,443
And remember that the seeking of oblivion is there because in oblivion there's no suffering.

349
00:33:03,047 --> 00:33:06,271
That's the relief of being in a deep sleep.

350
00:33:07,821 --> 00:33:12,588
So this craving is on these three levels.

351
00:33:12,969 --> 00:33:28,289
The level of sensual pleasure, the level of constantly becoming me in one form or another, constantly taking on different roles throughout the day, throughout my life, and at times just not wanting to be me one way or the other.

352
00:33:28,951 --> 00:33:31,654
So these are the cravings.

353
00:33:31,674 --> 00:33:32,496
And...

354
00:33:34,400 --> 00:33:41,068
Nibbana, he doesn't actually say Jesus is the end of suffering, is exactly the end of that craving.

355
00:33:42,131 --> 00:33:45,855
Now, this Nibbana is often difficult.

356
00:33:47,377 --> 00:33:58,093
The complete fading away and cessation of that same craving, the giving up and the relinquishing of it, freedom from it, no longer any reliance on it, this craving.

357
00:33:58,614 --> 00:34:03,681
But remember, what sustains the craving is that sense of self, is a sense of me.

358
00:34:04,623 --> 00:34:20,467
Now when it comes to Nibbana, he has various ways of explaining it, various images that he gives us.

359
00:34:21,048 --> 00:34:23,632
One is of an island, completely separate.

360
00:34:23,972 --> 00:34:24,733
One is of an island.

361
00:34:25,034 --> 00:34:28,420
So Nibbana is the island that we're making towards.

362
00:34:29,614 --> 00:34:33,059
He talks about an āyatana which is a sphere.

363
00:34:33,420 --> 00:34:41,331
A sphere in his language is a level of experience which is entire and complete unto itself.

364
00:34:41,351 --> 00:34:45,378
So for instance, there are six spheres dependent on our senses.

365
00:34:45,938 --> 00:34:51,706
So the eye, our visual capacity, is a sphere of experience.

366
00:34:51,686 --> 00:34:53,869
And you can't hear through it.

367
00:34:54,150 --> 00:34:57,235
You can't hear through your eyes and you can't taste through them.

368
00:34:57,856 --> 00:35:04,547
So all these senses are quite separate and they create certain levels of experience.

369
00:35:04,947 --> 00:35:08,552
And he says there is a level where none of this happens.

370
00:35:08,893 --> 00:35:11,697
There's no tasting, seeing, etc.

371
00:35:11,717 --> 00:35:16,985
There's no earth, there's no moon, there's no coming, there's no going, there's no staying still, etc.

372
00:35:16,965 --> 00:35:19,327
You can only stay still if you're coming and going.

373
00:35:19,708 --> 00:35:23,512
So it's a place which is completely transcendent.

374
00:35:23,532 --> 00:35:27,976
He talks about it as the unborn, the undying, the unconditioned, etc.

375
00:35:28,518 --> 00:35:30,300
And the word he uses there is ati.

376
00:35:30,960 --> 00:35:43,833
Ati means, when they ask him this quadrilemma, this is the big logical positions of the age, does the Buddha exist after he dies?

377
00:35:44,320 --> 00:35:45,681
Or does he not exist?

378
00:35:46,483 --> 00:35:48,947
Or does he exist and not exist?

379
00:35:49,588 --> 00:35:52,152
Or does he neither exist nor not exist?

380
00:35:52,431 --> 00:35:56,117
That's a killer.

381
00:35:56,438 --> 00:35:58,061
You can't go beyond those four.

382
00:35:58,621 --> 00:36:00,704
That's your logical proposition.

383
00:36:01,405 --> 00:36:05,072
Now the word in Pali which is used for that is ati.

384
00:36:05,411 --> 00:36:07,976
There is another word for is which is hoti.

385
00:36:08,336 --> 00:36:12,623
And hoti is like a joining word like when we say this is a clock.

386
00:36:13,766 --> 00:36:17,793
But he actually says ati, so there exists that which is not born nor died.

387
00:36:18,755 --> 00:36:29,413
But his most clear statement arises in one of the discourses when somebody approaches him and asks him, where is the end of the world?

388
00:36:30,074 --> 00:36:33,099
In other words, where is the end of the phenomenal world?

389
00:36:33,480 --> 00:36:39,690
Now, in those days, which is different from us, the world and consciousness were both the same thing.

390
00:36:40,902 --> 00:36:47,936
We are under the illusion that when we look at the world, we're actually seeing it as it is.

391
00:36:49,420 --> 00:36:59,079
That's to do with our upbringing and our so-called enlightenment and science, that we think that when we're looking at a tree, that's the way the tree really looks.

392
00:36:59,835 --> 00:37:06,704
But actually, it's totally dependent upon our eyes, our perceptual faculties, what our brain and minds do with it.

393
00:37:07,326 --> 00:37:13,393
And so if we were all to look at the same tree, we'd all be looking at a different tree.

394
00:37:14,114 --> 00:37:15,737
In this room, we're all in this room.

395
00:37:15,918 --> 00:37:22,586
Nobody would deny the room exists, but we all experience this room in our own particular way.

396
00:37:23,646 --> 00:37:26,610
So the world and consciousness were the same thing.

397
00:37:26,871 --> 00:37:31,735
Now what this man is asking is where does the world come to an end?

398
00:37:32,416 --> 00:37:35,740
Where does consciousness come to an end?

399
00:37:35,760 --> 00:37:38,284
And the Buddha says this question is not put properly.

400
00:37:38,443 --> 00:37:42,288
The question should be where does this world not find a footing?

401
00:37:44,130 --> 00:37:47,514
So our process is not the destruction of the world.

402
00:37:48,034 --> 00:37:49,856
It's to find this island.

403
00:37:50,242 --> 00:37:58,471
And then he says there is a consciousness which is not colored by any of the senses.

404
00:37:59,291 --> 00:38:01,074
So in Buddhism there are six senses.

405
00:38:01,333 --> 00:38:06,420
There's the five that we normally count and also the mind, the process within the mind.

406
00:38:06,440 --> 00:38:11,324
None of those can be found in this consciousness.

407
00:38:12,106 --> 00:38:15,489
He says that it is without boundary consciousness.

408
00:38:16,617 --> 00:38:21,505
Now, a boundary can only be created by phenomena, can only be created by objects, by things.

409
00:38:22,047 --> 00:38:23,250
So there's nothing there.

410
00:38:24,652 --> 00:38:31,284
And in all directions full of light, awakenedness, just this is the end of suffering.

411
00:38:32,007 --> 00:38:38,195
So this nibbana is not something which is some sort of idea.

412
00:38:38,376 --> 00:38:40,699
It's something to be personally experienced by us.

413
00:38:41,702 --> 00:38:44,606
And so how do we get to that experience?

414
00:38:45,568 --> 00:38:48,371
And this is the process of vipassana, you see.

415
00:38:48,833 --> 00:39:00,090
Now, so when you're sitting, when you're sitting and you're feeling and you're observing what's happening within you,

416
00:39:01,858 --> 00:39:06,335
unwittingly, we're making the inner world an object.

417
00:39:07,920 --> 00:39:12,036
I don't know whether you know this, but there was a woman called Margaret Marler.

418
00:39:12,215 --> 00:39:14,063
She was a student of Freud.

419
00:39:14,987 --> 00:39:18,693
And she studied babies, babies until the age of three.

420
00:39:19,594 --> 00:39:24,780
And she made these wonderful discoveries, which have been all reinforced since her.

421
00:39:24,800 --> 00:39:28,385
Whereas the first four months, there's no objects.

422
00:39:28,925 --> 00:39:37,476
All it is is a bath of information coming in, and the baby lives seemingly in a two-dimensional world.

423
00:39:38,398 --> 00:39:40,000
It doesn't have any depth.

424
00:39:40,586 --> 00:39:43,010
And that's why you get babies reaching out for rattles.

425
00:39:43,612 --> 00:39:46,177
They're actually creating a 3D world in doing so.

426
00:39:47,177 --> 00:39:52,005
And then round about four months, the first object looms out of all this information.

427
00:39:52,527 --> 00:39:54,731
And it's usually your carer, your mother.

428
00:39:55,693 --> 00:40:02,204
And then very slowly, all this information coming in is turned into this outer world.

429
00:40:02,885 --> 00:40:04,688
And it takes to the age of three.

430
00:40:05,090 --> 00:40:13,001
It takes three years for that child to come to know themselves as an individual separate from the world around them.

431
00:40:13,021 --> 00:40:16,605
That's why they're very clear about whether they're a boy or a girl and all that.

432
00:40:17,226 --> 00:40:18,628
It's like, that's it.

433
00:40:19,528 --> 00:40:31,164
Now, what we do then is we fall into that error of saying, well, look, that's the world out there and I'm me the way I experience the world.

434
00:40:32,072 --> 00:40:45,967
What we're doing is we are finding a position in ourselves to observe the inner world with all its information, which is the sensations in the body, all the emotions coming out from the heart, all the thoughts that are coming out.

435
00:40:45,987 --> 00:40:53,076
All of this we're actually pushing out just like that baby did with all the actual outer world.

436
00:40:53,536 --> 00:40:57,340
The inner world we're also pushing away from us.

437
00:40:57,360 --> 00:41:00,864
It's becoming an object to observe, to feel, to understand.

438
00:41:01,856 --> 00:41:06,123
And in so doing, again unwittingly, what is it that's pulling out?

439
00:41:06,784 --> 00:41:08,065
What is it that's pulling out?

440
00:41:08,746 --> 00:41:12,550
And that's when we begin to experience the observer within us very clearly.

441
00:41:12,931 --> 00:41:13,913
The one who knows.

442
00:41:14,333 --> 00:41:15,615
The observer, the feeler.

443
00:41:17,157 --> 00:41:23,947
And the observer is a mirror image.

444
00:41:25,409 --> 00:41:30,074
Because when you're in that state of clear observing, you...

445
00:41:31,692 --> 00:41:34,778
you're aware of yourself being the observer.

446
00:41:35,320 --> 00:41:35,922
Am I correct?

447
00:41:36,903 --> 00:41:37,746
Not vigorously, please.

448
00:41:40,012 --> 00:41:46,286
So, if you're aware of yourself being the observer, you see, you can't be that, can you?

449
00:41:48,692 --> 00:41:49,414
See?

450
00:41:50,507 --> 00:41:51,789
Yeah?

451
00:41:51,809 --> 00:42:20,514
Now, that's when you have to keep looking with an eagle eye, because at some point, whatever is in us, that is this nibbanic datu, to use the language of the scripture, of the Abhidhamma, the element of nibbana, right, to get that, to have it, to that experience, right, is being able to go beyond even the sense of the observer, the feeler.

452
00:42:20,494 --> 00:42:28,447
So there's these three, shall we say, backward movements which take us into an Ibanic experience.

453
00:42:28,469 --> 00:42:34,898
The first one is, as a child, we separate out from the world and become this individuated little being.

454
00:42:35,701 --> 00:42:45,878
Through our meditation, we're separating out from the inner world to become this individuated sense of the observer, the feeler, the one who knows.

455
00:42:45,858 --> 00:42:48,463
And it's just one step beyond that.

456
00:42:49,083 --> 00:42:52,409
Even now, we could just step behind and that'd be it.

457
00:42:54,434 --> 00:42:58,541
So, that's the process of liberation.

458
00:42:58,561 --> 00:43:04,052
The process of liberation is simply letting go of these three worlds.

459
00:43:04,807 --> 00:43:09,295
And remember that when the Buddha was fully liberated, he didn't disappear.

460
00:43:10,057 --> 00:43:14,706
He didn't sit by the roadside there with a sign saying, fully liberated, do not disturb.

461
00:43:14,766 --> 00:43:18,512
It's like he re-entered the world.

462
00:43:18,552 --> 00:43:24,744
He re-entered the world, the phenomenal world, and was able to pass on his message to others.

463
00:43:25,184 --> 00:43:28,891
So what do we lose in the end through this process, you see?

464
00:43:28,871 --> 00:43:35,641
So when the Buddha, because of the negative way he would talk about Nibbana, he was often accused of being an annihilationist.

465
00:43:36,422 --> 00:43:43,429
And he insisted, he said, no, he said the only thing that's annihilated is greed, hatred and delusion.

466
00:43:43,811 --> 00:43:46,333
All the rest is given back purified.

467
00:43:50,960 --> 00:43:52,601
Now that, I think, is a joyful message.

468
00:43:55,179 --> 00:43:58,224
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

469
00:43:59,226 --> 00:44:13,188
May you, by your fierce determination to achieve liberation, finally arrive at that heavenly place sooner rather than later.

